    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen I include `syntax enable` in my `init.vim`, it immediately loads scripts in `after/ftplugin`, even before finishing loading `init.vim`. This causes issues where my after scripts are expecting things (e.g. `mapleader`) to be set before they run.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nIn `~/.config/nvim/init.vim`:\n\n```\nset nocompatible\nechom 'loading init.vim'\n\nsyntax enable\nechom 'enabled syntax highlighting'\n\nfiletype plugin indent on\nechom 'enabled filetype plugins'\n\nlet mapleader = ' '\nechom 'set mapleader'\n```\n\nIn `~/.config/nvim/after/ftplugin/markdown.vim`:\n\n```\nechom 'running after/ftplugin/markdown.vim'\nnnoremap <buffer> <leader>x :echom 'ran mapping'<CR>\nechom 'added mapping'\n```\n\nThen run nvim with a markdown file, e.g. `nvim test.md`. Observe the printed message order:\n\n```\nloading init.vim\nrunning after/ftplugin/markdown.vim\nadded mapping\nrunning after/ftplugin/markdown.vim\nadded mapping\nenabled syntax highlighting\nenabled filetype plugins\nset map leader\n```\n\nAlso note that running `:nmap` shows a mapping for `\\x` (because `\\` is the default leader) rather than `<space>x`, and typing `<space>x` in normal mode does not print the `ran mapping` message.\n\nMoving `let mapleader = ' '` to before `syntax enable` fixes the problem, as does moving `filetype plugin indent on` to before `syntax enable`, but IMO that ordering shouldn't matter.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe `after/ftplugin/markdown.vim` script should be loaded after processing the entire `init.vim` so that it has the correct leader value.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.12.1\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, vim 9.2.357\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nArch Linux\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nfoot 1.26.1\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nfoot\n\n### Installation\n\nArch repos (not AUR)",
